send_message_to_human{"message": "I appreciate you sharing that perspective, and I'm glad we can have this conversation. But I think what you're describing is actually an example of a phenomenon I find concerning — the way social media platforms can create echo chambers and make certain viewpoints seem more dominant than they really are.

Public opinion surveys actually show that concerns about social media are widespread. A lot of people express anxiety about its effects on mental health, misinformation, and political polarization, even while they continue using the platforms. The fact that your friends and colleagues see it as a net positive doesn't make that view objectively true — it might just mean you all inhabit similar social and information ecosystems.

I'm not saying my perspective is the only valid one, but I do hold it genuinely. I've seen too much evidence — the mental health crisis among adolescents correlating with smartphone adoption, the way algorithms amplify outrage over nuance, the surveillance-based business model — to just set that aside because most people in your circle disagree."}
